{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15352"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15352"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.16,0.5,0.13,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67138"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8043"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52594"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6965"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"8762"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22465"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67138"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-week-old neonate presents with persistent jaundice, pale stools, and dark urine. The infant was born at term with no complications during pregnancy or delivery. Whatever the underlying cause, this could lead to chronic liver disease. Occasionally this may require liver transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the commonest reason for liver transplantation in children?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alagille syndrome","Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency","Biliary atresia","Progressive familial intrahepatic cholestasis","Wilson disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare disease affecting 1 in 10,000 to 1 in 20,000 live births worldwide. It is characterised by progressive inflammation and fibrosis of both intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts, leading to cholestasis and cirrhosis if untreated. The aim of treatment is to decompress the biliary system and this can usually be done with a portoenterostomy. Should that fail, a liver transplant may be required. Biliary atresia is the most common cause of chronic liver disease and liver transplantation in children, accounting for approximately 40-50% of paediatric liver transplants. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlagille syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder affecting multiple organ systems, including the liver, but is less common. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause liver disease in children but accounts for a smaller percentage of transplants. \u003Cstrong\u003EProgressive familial intrahepatic cholestasis\u003C/strong\u003E represents a group of genetic disorders that can lead to liver failure but is relatively rare. \u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in older children or young adults and can be managed with medical therapy in many cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Biliary atresia is the most common cause of chronic liver disease and liver transplantation in children.","Biliary atresia presents with progressive jaundice and pale stools in the first few months of life.","Early surgical intervention (Kasai procedure) is crucial for better outcomes in biliary atresia."],"references":["Smith SK, Miloh T. Pediatric Liver Transplantation. Clin Liver Dis. 2022 Aug;26(3):521-535. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2022.03.010. PMID: 35868688.","Ovchinsky N, Moreira RK, Lefkowitch JH, Lavine JE. Liver biopsy in modern clinical practice: a pediatric point-of-view. Adv Anat Pathol. 2012 Jul;19(4):250-62. doi: 10.1097/PAP.0b013e31825c6a20. PMID: 22692288; PMCID: PMC3404724.","Finegold MJ. Common diagnostic problems in pediatric liver pathology. Clin Liver Dis. 2002 May;6(2):421-54. doi: 10.1016/s1089-3261(02)00014-4. PMID: 12122864."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52594"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52594"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T16:57:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T16:58:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67138"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta